snippet.textDisplay:
Nice... I always have found power supply connectors hard to deal with after they are installed. So if you had to add a GPU or your GPU upgrade required more power then you all most have to deinstall the power supply to run a new or second connector.

Then next step to this evolution is to have the power bus integrated into the case, so power supply manufacturers only have to provide the main power supply unit and the power bus would be pre configured to your case. This would make its cases even smaller with pre routed cables. Nice part about going this direction is starting to integrate hot swappable SATA connectors where not only do you get a clean look, but also functionality only found in server grade equipment.

snippet.textDisplay:
Sooooooooo ... what's the point of that thing in the first place?
It doesn't make your cables less thick - still a beefy 24pin cable and other stuff going on.
The 20pin "bridge" from the PSU to the hub is way too short in order to justify ANY "advantage". For example:
Let's put this monster of a hub in the front where a big old Drivebay would reside. Yeah - the connection cable won't reach it.
So I consider this a fail.
Additional bonus: There are active components in the hub that will heat up and if you put them in a rats nest of RGB Cables where no airflow is coming through, it might get toasty.
I'll stick with a conventional PSU, thanks.
If the main power supply would be as tiny as an SFX psu or something like that, I would consider it feasable in order to get some serious custom stuff going on (Full ATX hardware in a tiny media-center PC, anyone?). But as a replacement for an existing ATX-Supply in an ATX-Case? Nah - thanks.
